Phenotypic plasticity has been considered to be the primary feature enabling aliens to colonize new, environmentally diverse areas (
 Richards et al., 2006; 
 Molina-Montenegro, Atala & Gianoli, 2010). However, recent research has indicated that alien plants can evolve quickly in newly occupied areas, so both phenotypic plasticity and evolution of reproductive features could be relevant factors for successful invasions (
 Geng et al., 2007; 
 Molina-Montenegro et al., 2018).
